# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2014-commonwealth-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The **1930 British Empire Games** were the inaugural edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, and was held in Hamilton, Ontario, from 16 to 23 August 1930.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was organized by *Hamilton Spectator* sportswriter Bobby Robinson after he attended the 1928 Summer Olympics in Amsterdam as manager of the Canadian track and field team and was inspired to create a similar event for the British Empire.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] After campaigning for the idea among contacts he met at the Olympics, he was asked to organise the first British Empire Games in Hamilton.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Fellow Hamilton journalist Ivan Miller helped with the organizing committee.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The sports included athletics, boxing, lawn bowls, rowing, swimming, and wrestling.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony and athletics events were held at Civic Stadium (later renamed Ivor Wynne Stadium) in east Hamilton.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The event was opened by the Governor General of Canada, Lord Willingdon, on 16 August.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] Canadian triple jumper Gordon Smallacombe claimed the debut gold medal a few hours later.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] The 1930 British Empire Games made use of pedestals for dignitaries to present medals to winning athletes, as proposed by Bobby Robinson.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1930-british-empire-games] This inspired the Olympic medal podium ceremonies which began at the 1932 Winter Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The **1934 British Empire Games** were the second edition of what is now known as the Commonwealth Games, held in England, from 4–11 August 1934.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The host city was London, with the main venues at Wembley Park and the White City Stadium, although the track cycling events were in Manchester.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Seventeen national teams took part, including the Irish Free State (the only Games in which they participated, although an all-Ireland team competed at the 1930 Games).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The 1934 Games had been originally awarded to Johannesburg, South Africa, but the change of venue to London was made due to concerns regarding the treatment of black and Asian athletes by South African officials and fans.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Six sports were featured in the Games with rowing being dropped from 1930 but cycling making its first appearance.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Athletics took place at the White City Stadium, while boxing, wrestling, and aquatics (swimming and diving) were held at the Wembley Empire Pool, where the swimming pool would be converted overnight into an arena with 7,000 additional seats brought in to increase the capacity to 12,000.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Lawn bowls was held at two clubs in Paddington and Temple, while the cycling was held at the Fallowfield Stadium in Manchester.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] Events for women athletes included a debut in athletics; the previous games had women's events in swimming and diving only.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] The Wembley Empire Pool was built specifically for the games on the instruction of Arthur Elvin and had been completed in just nine months, opening 10 days before the start of the Games on 25 July.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1934-british-empire-games] (Teams participating for the first time in **bold**).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The **1938 British Empire Games** were the third British Empire Games, the event that evolved to become the Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Held in Sydney, Australia, from 5–12 February 1938, they were timed to coincide with Sydney's sesqui-centenary (150 years since the foundation of British settlement in Australia).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Venues included the Sydney Cricket Ground (the main stadium), the North Sydney Olympic Pool and Henson Park.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] An estimated 40,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] A men's residential village was established within the grounds of the Sydney Showground, while the female athletes were housed in hotels.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] The star of the games was the Australian athlete Decima Norman, who won five gold medals in track and field.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Margaret Dovey, later married to Australian prime minister Gough Whitlam, finished sixth in the 220 yards breaststroke.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1938-british-empire-games] Due to the onset of World War II, the games were not held again until 1950.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The **1948 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XIV Olympiad** and officially branded as **London 1948**, were an international multi-sport event held from 29 July to 14 August 1948 in London, United Kingdom.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Following a twelve-year hiatus caused by the outbreak of World War II, these were the first Summer Olympics held since the 1936 Games in Berlin.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1940 Olympic Games had been scheduled for Tokyo and then for Helsinki, while the 1944 Olympic Games had been provisionally planned for London.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second time London hosted the Olympic Games, having previously hosted them in 1908, making it the second city to host the Summer Olympics twice (after Paris).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The Olympics would return again to London 64 years later in 2012, making London the first city to host the games three times, and the only such city until Paris, who hosted their third games in 2024, and Los Angeles, who will host theirs in 2028.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympic Games were also the first of two summer Games held under the IOC presidency of Sigfrid Edström.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1940s, as the 1940 and 1944 Summer Olympics were cancelled due to World War II.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] It was also the first Summer Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games" due to the difficult economic climate and the rationing imposed in the aftermath of World War II.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] A record 59 nations were represented by 4,104 athletes, 3,714 men, and 390 women in 19 sport disciplines.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan were not invited to participate in the games; the Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Israel requested to participate (symbolically represented by Raya Bronstein and Frieda Berson-Lichtblau) but was denied as the International Olympic Committee did not yet recognize the country, while the Olympic mandate of Palestine expired.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] This in turn shifted the view of the Arab countries who had intended to boycott the event and now decided to take part.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] One of the star performers at the 1948 Games was Dutch sprinter Fanny Blankers-Koen.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Dubbed the "Flying Housewife", the thirty-year-old mother of two won four gold medals in athletics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias of the United States became the youngest male ever to win an Olympic track and field gold medal at the age of seventeen.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The most individual medals were won by Veikko Huhtanen of Finland, who took three golds, a silver and a bronze in men's gymnastics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States topped the medal table.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1939, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1944 Olympic Summer Games to London, ahead of Rome, Detroit, Budapest, Lausanne, Helsinki, Montreal and Athens.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] World War II stopped the plans and the Games were cancelled so London again stood as a candidate for 1948.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain almost handed the 1948 games to the United States due to post-war financial and rationing problems, but King George VI said that hosting the Olympics would help to restore Britain from World War II.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The official report of the London Olympics shows that London was not pressed to run the Games against its will.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] and saw the president of the International Olympic Committee to discuss the question of London being chosen for this great event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] As a result, an investigating committee was set up by the British Olympic Council to work out in some detail the possibility of holding the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] should be invited to apply for the allocation of the Games in 1948.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1946 the IOC, through a postal vote, gave the summer Games to London and the winter competition to St Moritz.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] London was selected ahead of Baltimore, Minneapolis, Lausanne, Los Angeles, and Philadelphia.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] London, which had previously hosted the 1908 Summer Olympics, became the second city to host the Olympics twice; Paris hosted the event in 1900 and 1924.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] London later became the first city to host the Olympics for a third time when the city hosted the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley, a gold medal winner at the 1928 Olympics, member of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), and president of the Amateur Athletics Association was named Chairman of the Organising and Executive Committees.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The other members of the committees were: Colonel Evan Hunter, General Secretary of the British Olympic Association, and Chief de mission for Great Britain; Lord Aberdare, the other British member of the IOC; Sir Noel Curtis-Bennett; Alderman H.E.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Emrys Lloyd, who became the committee's legal advisor; C.B.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Cowley of the London Press and Advertising; R.B.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Studdert, managing director of the Army & Navy Stores; A.E.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Porritt, a member of the IOC for New Zealand who resided in London; S.F.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Rous, Secretary of The Football Association; and Jack Beresford.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms were introduced for the first time.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] There were twenty of them—one for each Olympic sport and three separate pictograms for the arts competition, the opening ceremony and the closing ceremony.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] They were called "Olympic symbols" and intended for use on tickets.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The background of each pictogram resembled an escutcheon.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms appeared again 16 years later, and were used at all subsequent Summer Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] At the time of the Games, food, petrol and building were still subject to the rationing imposed during the war in Britain; because of this the 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Athletes were given the same increased rations as dockers and miners, 5,467 calories a day instead of the normal 2,600.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Building an Olympic Village was deemed too expensive, and athletes were housed in existing accommodation.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Male competitors stayed at RAF camps in Uxbridge and West Drayton, and an Army camp in Richmond Park; female competitors in London colleges.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley unfurled the Olympic Flag at the Richmond Park camp at an opening ceremony in July as Minister of Works, Charles Key, declared the camp open.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] These were the first games to be held following the death of Pierre de Coubertin, founder of the International Olympic Committee, in 1937.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] They were also the last to include an arts competition, which took place at the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nicknamed "relay of peace" due to crossing through several countries in Europe to represent their union after the Second World War, the torch relay for these games took place from 17 to 29 July 1948, with a distance of 3,160 kilometres (1,960 mi) and 1,416 torchbearers.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] There were three types of torches: the standard one made of aluminium and powered by solid fuel, a special one powered by butane gas (used aboard HMS *Whitesand Bay*) and a third one used in the Wembley stadium, made of stainless steel and powered by a magnesium candle.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The journey began with the lighting of the flame in Olympia.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the civil war taking place in Greece, the Greek part of the relay went directly to Corfu, where HMS *Whitesand Bay* picked the flame to transport it to Bari.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] From there, the flame crossed Italy, Switzerland, France, Luxembourg and Belgium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] After a boat trip from Calais to Dover (aboard of HMS *Bicester*), the flame traveled to several towns in Southeast England until the arrival at Wembley for the Opening ceremony.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Army bands began playing at 2 pm for the 85,000 spectators in Empire Stadium at Wembley Park.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The international and national organisers arrived at 2.35 pm and King George VI and Queen Elizabeth, with Queen Mary and other members of the Royal Family, at 2.45 pm.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Fifteen minutes later the competitors entered the stadium in a procession that took 50 minutes.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The last team was that of the United Kingdom.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] A visionary dream has today become a glorious reality.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] At the end of the worldwide struggle in 1945, many institutions and associations were found to have withered and only the strongest had survived.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] How, many wondered, had the great Olympic Movement prospered?
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] At 4 pm, the time shown on the clock tower on the London Games symbol, the King declared the Games open, 2,500 pigeons were set free and the Olympic Flag raised to its 35 ft (11 m) flagpole at the end of the stadium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The Royal Horse Artillery sounded a 21-gun salute to welcome the last runner in the Torch Relay: John Mark, a British track and field sprinter and student at the University of Cambridge with impressive Olympian good looks.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Mark ran a lap of the track – created with cinders from the domestic coal fires of Leicester – and climbed the steps to the Olympic cauldron.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] After saluting the crowd, he turned and lit the flame.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] After more speeches, Donald Finlay of the British team (given his RAF rank of Wing Commander) took the Olympic Oath on behalf of all competitors.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The National Anthem was sung and the massed athletes turned and marched out of the stadium, led by Greece, tailed by Britain.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Thus were launched the Olympic Games of London, under the most happy auspices.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony and over 60 hours of Games coverage was broadcast live on BBC television, which was then officially available only in the London area.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] However, the BBC's transmissions could be received much further away in the right conditions, and some of the Games were watched by at least one viewer in the Channel Islands.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC's official report on the coverage estimated that an average of half a million viewers watched each of their Olympic broadcasts.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC paid £1,000 for the broadcasting rights.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Of the live television coverage, only a small section of the opening ceremony broadcast still exists in the archives.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] However, various filmed reports shot for the BBC's *Television Newsreel* program do also still exist.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics featured 136 medal events, covering 23 disciplines in 17 different sports and in arts.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] These Games also included Lacrosse and Swedish (Ling) gymnastics as demonstration sports.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Empire Stadium was the venue for 33 athletics events at the Games; 24 for men and nine for women.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Of these, four were making their Olympic debut – the men's 10 km walk, and the women's 200 metres, long jump and shot put.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] A total of 754 athletes from 53 countries participated in athletics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Fanny Blankers-Koen of the Netherlands, a 30-year-old mother of two children nicknamed "The Flying Housewife", won four gold medals, in the 100 metres, 200 metres, 80 metre hurdles, and 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] As world record holder in the long jump and high jump Blankers-Koen may have been able to win further medals but, at this time, female athletes were limited to three individual events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Duncan White won the first medal of any kind for Sri Lanka (then Ceylon) when he finished second in the 400 metre hurdles.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Arthur Wint became the first Jamaican to win an Olympic gold medal, in the men's 400 metres; he also won silver in the men's 800 metres.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Audrey Patterson became the first African-American woman to win a medal, winning bronze in a track and field event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] A few days later Alice Coachman became the first woman of colour in the world and the first African-American woman to win a gold medal in track and field in the history of the modern Olympics with a jump of 1.68 m (5' 61⁄4").
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] She also was the only American woman to win an athletics gold medal during the 1948 Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The marathon saw a dramatic finish with the first man to enter the stadium, Etienne Gailly of Belgium, exhausted and nearly unable to run.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] While he was struggling, Argentinian athlete Delfo Cabrera and Tom Richards of Great Britain passed him, with Cabrera winning the gold medal and Richards obtaining the silver.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Gailly managed to recover enough to cross the line for the bronze.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The decathlon was won by 17-year-old Bob Mathias of the United States.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Categories: sports-related architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] These Olympics were the last time art competitions were considered Olympic events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Basketball made its second appearance as a medal sport, appearing as an indoor competition for the first time after poor weather disrupted the matches at the 1936 Berlin Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The event, for men only, was contested by 23 nations split into four pools for the preliminary round; the top two in each pool advanced to the quarterfinals with the other teams entering playoffs for the minor placings.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States and France reached the final which was won by the Americans 65–21 to claim the gold medal.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second of the United States' seven consecutive gold medals in Olympic men's and women's basketball.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Brazil defeated Mexico 52–47 to claim bronze.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eight different classifications were contested ranging from flyweight, for boxers weighing less than 51 kg, to heavyweight, for boxers over 80 kg.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] South Africa, Argentina and Hungary each won two gold medals.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men and one for women.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that a women's canoeing event had been contested in the Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won four gold medals (two by Gert Fredriksson) and Czechoslovakia three.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested – two road bicycle racing events and four track cycling events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] No women's cycling events were contested.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] France won three gold medals and Italy two, while Great Britain captured five medals overall, but none were gold.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Four diving events were contested, two for men, and two for women.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The events are labelled as 3 metre springboard and 10 metre platform by the International Olympic Committee but appeared on the 1948 Official Report as *springboard diving* and *highboard diving*, respectively.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] All four gold medals, and 10 out of 12 awarded in total, were won by the United States.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Victoria Manalo Draves, who won both gold medals in the women's events, and Sammy Lee, who took a gold and a bronze in the men's events, became the first Asian Americans to win gold medals at an Olympic Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Six gold medals were awarded in equestrian, individual and team dressage, individual and team eventing and individual and team show jumping.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Harry Llewellyn and Foxhunter, who would claim a gold medal in Helsinki, won bronze in the team jumping event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Seven events were contested, six for men and one for women.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Ilona Elek, who had won the women's foil competition in Berlin, was one of only two competitors to successfully defend an Olympic title in London.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Elek's sister, Margit, placed sixth in the same event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Edoardo Mangiarotti won three medals, two silver and a bronze, having previously won a gold medal in the 1936 Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Throughout his career the Italian won 13 Olympic fencing medals and 27 world championship medals, both of which remain records.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen nations participated in the field hockey competition.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was ultimately won by India, who defeated Great Britain to claim the country's first gold medal as an independent nation under captain Kishan Lal and Vice-Captain Kunwar Digvijay Singh.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen teams entered the football competition at these Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the rise of the professional game during the 12 years since the Berlin Olympics the number of talented amateurs for teams to select from was reduced.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The gold medal was won by Sweden, who defeated Yugoslavia 3–1 in the final.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Denmark defeated hosts Great Britain, managed by Matt Busby of Manchester United, 5–3 to win the bronze medal.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the tournament's 18 matches a total of 102 goals were scored; an average 5.66 goals per match.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The joint top scorers with seven goals each were Gunnar Nordahl of Sweden and Denmark's John Hansen.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nordahl and Swedish teammates Gunnar Gren and Nils Liedholm went on to play for A.C.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Milan and together were nicknamed Gre-No-Li.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first international football tournament ever to be broadcast on television, with the two semi-finals, the bronze medal match and the final all being shown live in full by the BBC.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men, and one for women.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the men's pommel horse, a tie was declared between three competitors, all Finns, and no medals other than gold were awarded in this event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Finland won six gold medals overall, and Switzerland three.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Lacrosse was an exhibition sport at these Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] An English team composed of players from various universities played a U.S. team represented by Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute at the Empire Stadium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Only one modern pentathlon event was contested, the five component sports– riding, fencing, shooting, swimming, and running- being held over six days.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Scoring was by point-for-place system across the five phases with the winner being the athlete with the lowest combined ranking.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The sport's international federation, the Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne was founded during the Games, on 3 August 1948.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won two medals in the event; William Grut won the gold, with a final points total of 16, and Gösta Gärdin took bronze.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] American George Moore won the silver medal.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Seven rowing events were contested, all open to men only.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain and the United States each claimed two gold medals.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The events were held on the River Thames at Henley, over the same course as the Henley Royal Regatta.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The sailing events at the Games took place in Torquay, in the southwest of Great Britain.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Five events were contested, with the United States winning four total medals.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] One of host nation Great Britain's three gold medals at the Games came in the Swallow class from Stewart Morris and David Bond.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the Firefly class Danish sailor Paul Elvstrøm won gold the despite the Danish Olympic Committee having misgivings about sending him to compete as the 18-year-old could speak no English.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first of four consecutive Olympics with a gold medal for Elvstrøm.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Four events were contested, all open to both men and women, although all medals were won by men.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the 50 metre rifle, prone position, only two points separated the top three competitors.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Károly Takács had been a member of the Hungary's world champion pistol shooting team in 1938 when a grenade shattered his right hand – his pistol hand.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Takács taught himself to shoot with his left hand and, 10 years after his injury, he won an Olympic gold medal in the rapid-fire pistol event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eleven events were contested, six for men and five for women.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won eight gold medals, including all six men's events, and 15 medals in total.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen nations fielded a team in these games, which were ultimately won by Italy, who were undefeated throughout.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was conducted in a mult-tier bracket, with the best four teams from the group stages participating in a final round-robin bracket.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Silver was claimed by Hungary, and bronze by the Netherlands.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested, all for men only.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] These games marked the addition of the bantamweight class to the Olympic programme, the first change to the programme since 1920.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won four gold medals, and eight overall; the remaining two gold medals were claimed by Egypt.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Sixteen wrestling events were held, eight Greco-Roman and eight freestyle.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Both categories were dominated by two nations.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Turkey was the most successful nation with six gold medals followed by Sweden receiving 5 gold medals.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] These two teams claimed 24 total medals, in other words half of the total medals given.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] London was the first Olympics to have a political defection.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Marie Provazníková, the 57-year-old Czechoslovak President of the International Gymnastics Federation, refused to return home, citing "lack of freedom" after the Czechoslovak coup in February led to the country's inclusion in the Soviet Bloc.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] For the 1948 Olympics, the Technicolor Corporation devised a bipack colour filming process – dubbed "Technichrome" – whereby hundreds of hours of film documented the events in colour, without having to use expensive and heavy Technicolor cameras.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Slightly over 2,000 journalists attended the 1948 Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] A cinder track was laid inside Empire Stadium and all other venues were adapted.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] For the first time at the Olympics swimming events were held undercover, at the 8000 capacity Empire Pool.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] As the pool was longer than the standard Olympic length of 50 metres a platform was constructed across the pool which both shortened it and housed officials.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In 2010 one of the last remaining venues from the Games, the Herne Hill Velodrome where cycling events were staged, was saved when a new 15-year lease was agreed meaning that repairs could take place.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Campaigners and users of the track had feared that it would be forced to close as it was in desperate need of refurbishment.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen made their first official appearance: British Guiana (now Guyana), Burma (now Myanmar), Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), Iraq, Jamaica, Korea, Lebanon, Pakistan, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Syria, Trinidad and Tobago, and Venezuela.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] It was the first time that Australia, New Zealand, Philippines, India and Pakistan competed as fully independent nations at the Olympic Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan, under Allied military occupations, were not allowed to send athletes to the games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Due to continuing labour shortages, German prisoners of war were used for the construction of the facilities for the games, in particular Olympic Way.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Italy, although originally an Axis power, had defected to the Allies in 1943 following Benito Mussolini being deposed, and was allowed to send athletes.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The nations that returned to the games were Cuba, Iran (The last participation of a Persian athlete was in Paris 1900), Ireland, Panama and Spain.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Other nations, besides Germany and Japan, that participated in the previous games in Berlin 1936 but were absent in London 1948 were Bolivia, Bulgaria, Costa Rica, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] In the case of the Baltic nations, they had been occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union, only returning to the games many decades later.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Bulgaria, Romania and Mandatory Palestine accepted invitations for the Games but withdrew a few days before it began.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico, an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States, made its Olympic debut as an independent team.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] Bermuda, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago, Singapore and British Guyana were part of the British Empire.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1948 Summer Games, ranked by number of gold medals won.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1948-summer-olympics] The host nation was 12th, with 27 medals, including four golds.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The **1950 British Empire Games** were the fourth staging of what is now called the Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] It was held in Auckland, New Zealand, between 4 and 11 February 1950, after a 12-year gap from the third edition of the games due to World War II.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The fourth games were originally awarded to Montreal, Canada and were to be held in 1942 but were cancelled due to the War.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The Games were declared open by Sir Bernard Freyberg.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] The opening ceremony was held at Eden Park and was sold out with 40,000 people attending.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Eden Park also served as the main venue, while the closing ceremonies were held at Western Springs Stadium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] Other venues included the Auckland Town Hall and the Newmarket Olympic Pool.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] A 1950 British Empire Games documentary film of the games was made by the New Zealand National Film Unit.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1950-british-empire-games] At the 1950 British Empire Games all the teams won at least one medal.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Vancouver, British Columbia, from 30 July to 7 August 1954.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the fifth edition of the event that would eventually become known as the Commonwealth Games, the second post-war Games, the second Canadian Games after the inaugural event in Hamilton and the first event since the name change from British Empire Games took effect in 1952.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Other bids to stage the Games were received from Toronto, Montreal and Hamilton.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The main venue was the Empire Stadium, which had been specifically constructed for the games at the cost of £500,000.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Work on the 25,000 seated stadium started in October 1953 and the keys were handed over to Stan Smith (General chairman of the games) on 12 July 1954.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The games were attended by 24 nations and 662 competitors.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was the first time that the games gained a television audience, when CBC and NBC transmitted pictures to an estimated 100 million North American viewers.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Recordings of the games were also shown on the BBC Television Service, beginning a consistent association between the BBC and the Commonwealth Games which only ended in 2026.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was at these games that the "Miracle Mile" took place between Roger Bannister and John Landy at the Empire Stadium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] This was the first time these two (and at that time the only two) sub-four-minute mile runners appeared in the same race, and also the first time two runners broke four minutes in the same race.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] On the same afternoon, Jim Peters, the holder of the world best time for the marathon, entered the stadium 17 minutes ahead of his nearest rival, but collapsed on his final lap, and never completed the race.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/1954-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 24 teams were represented at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The **2014 Commonwealth Games**, officially known as the **XX Commonwealth Games** and commonly known as **Glasgow 2014** were an international multi-sport event celebrated in the tradition of the Commonwealth Games as governed by the Commonwealth Games Federation (CGF).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] It took place in Glasgow, Scotland, from 23 July to 3 August 2014.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow was selected as the host city on 9 November 2007 during CGF General Assembly in Colombo, Sri Lanka, defeating Abuja, Nigeria.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] It was the largest multi-sport event ever held in Scotland with around 4,950 athletes from 71 different nations and territories competing in 18 different sports, outranking the 1970 and 1986 Commonwealth Games in Edinburgh.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Games received acclaim for their organisation, attendance, and the public enthusiasm of the people of Scotland, with CGF chief executive Mike Hooper hailing them as "the standout games in the history of the movement".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Held in Scotland for the third time, the Games were notable for the successes of the Home Nations of the United Kingdom, with England, Wales and hosts Scotland achieving their largest ever gold medal hauls and overall medal hauls at a Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] England finished top of the medal table for the first time since the 1986 Commonwealth Games, also held in Scotland.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Kiribati also won its first ever medal at a Commonwealth Games, a gold in the 105 kg men's weightlifting competition.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] These were the final Commonwealth Games to be opened by Elizabeth II; the final two Games of her reign, in 2018 and 2022 were opened by her son, then-Prince of Wales Charles III.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Scotland was the first country to consider hosting the 2014 Commonwealth Games in 2004, with Scottish cities being invited by the Commonwealth Games Council for Scotland to consider making a bid.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] In September 2004, Glasgow was announced as the Scottish candidate city over Edinburgh (which hosted the Games in 1970 and 1986, and the inaugural Commonwealth Youth Games in 2000) following a cost-benefit analysis by the Commonwealth Games Council for Scotland.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Scottish Executive under then First Minister of Scotland, Jack McConnell, with the support of the United Kingdom government and all main parties in the Scottish Parliament, formally announced Glasgow's intention to host the games on 16 August 2005.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] In March 2006, the bidding process began, with the Glasgow Bidding team presenting their case to the Commonwealth Games Federation at the 2006 Commonwealth Games in Melbourne, along with the other confirmed candidate cities; the Nigerian capital, Abuja and Halifax in Canada.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] In October 2006, the first voting delegates arrived in Glasgow, to inspect the city's existing and proposed amenities and facilities.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow announced on 16 January 2007, the 17 sports to be included should its bid be successful.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Halifax later withdrew its bid on 8 March 2007, following the withdrawal of funding from the municipal government.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] That left Abuja and Glasgow as the remaining bidders, with Abuja seen as a likely favourite due to the basis of its campaign that an African nation has never before hosted the Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The deadline for formal submission of bids to the Commonwealth Games Federation, in the form of a Candidate City File, was set for May 2007.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Commonwealth Games Evaluation Commission concluded that: "Glasgow has shown it has the ability to stage the 2014 Commonwealth Games to a standard which would continue to enhance the image and prestige of the Games." This put Glasgow ahead in terms of the technical comprehensiveness of its bid.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The final decision on the host city of the 2014 Commonwealth Games was held in Colombo, Sri Lanka on 9 November 2007 at the Commonwealth Games Federation General Assembly, attended by all 71 Commonwealth Games member associations.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Each bid city made a presentation to the General Assembly, the order of which was determined by drawing lots.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow's delegation was led by Louise Martin, chair of the Commonwealth Games Council for Scotland, First Minister Alex Salmond, athlete Jamie Quarry and Leader of Glasgow City Council Steven Purcell.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The presentation also included a promotional film narrated by Sean Connery.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Abuja's delegation was led by General Yakubu Gowon, head of the Abuja 2014 Commonwealth Games bid team.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The CGF members later voted for their preferred candidate in a secret ballot.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] As there were only two bids, the winner was announced by the CGF President, Mike Fennel, after the first round of voting, with the winner only requiring a simple majority.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Glasgow 2014 Organising Committee was responsible for organising and delivering the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] It was established as a limited company whose members included the Scottish Government, Glasgow City Council and Commonwealth Games Scotland.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow City Council was responsible for delivering a number of the venues and lasting benefits from the Games for the city and people of Glasgow.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Scottish Government was the third organisation in the partnership and was the main funder of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Lord Robert Smith was the chairman of the Glasgow 2014 Organising Committee.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Celtic Park hosted for the opening ceremony of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Commonwealth Arena and Sir Chris Hoy Velodrome precinct, situated at Parkhead in the East End of the city, hosted the Badminton as well as Track cycling.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow Green was the starting point for the free Athletics (Marathon), Cycling (Road Race) and Cycling (Time Trial) events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow Green was the venue for Field hockey and saw the construction of a new Glasgow Green Hockey Centre.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Tollcross International Swimming Centre, was the venue for Swimming events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] It already had one Olympic standard 50 metre swimming pool, which was extensively upgraded, and a second 50-metre pool was added for the Games as a warm-up facility.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The existing permanent seating capacity was increased by 1,000.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Combined with additional temporary seating the venue had over 5,000 seats for the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Ibrox Stadium, in the South Side, was the venue for the Rugby Sevens tournament.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Mountain biking was held on the Cathkin Braes in Rutherglen, the Royal Burgh neighbouring the city.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Hampden Park hosted all the track and field events as well as the closing ceremony.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Clyde Auditorium hosted Weightlifting, whilst the new OVO Hydro was used for the Gymnastics and Netball events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Kelvingrove Park, also in the city's West End, was the venue for Bowls and has five bowling greens installed for competitive use.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] A comprehensive upgrade and refurbishment of the park was completed ahead of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Scotstoun Leisure Centre hosted Table tennis and Squash.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Shooting competitions took place at the Ministry of Defence full-bore rifle and clay target ranges at Barry Buddon, near Dundee, which were also used in the 1986 Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] There were temporary ranges built for the small-bore rifle and pistol events.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Diving was held at the Royal Commonwealth Pool in Edinburgh, located 45 miles (72 km) to the east, which held the annual Edinburgh Festival at the same time as the 2014 Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Strathclyde Country Park, beside Hamilton and Motherwell, hosted the Triathlon event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Athletes' Village for the 2014 Commonwealth Games was situated on a 35-hectare (86-acre) site, in Dalmarnock, Glasgow.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Primarily the site was used as accommodation for the athletes competing in the games as well as team officials from every competing nation for the duration of the games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] As well as accommodation, the athletes' village also housed a retail zone, dining hall, medical facilities, gym, religious centre and recreational spaces.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The countdown clock was unveiled at the Glasgow Central Station on 10 March 2014 during the Commonwealth Day.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The clock was sponsored by the Swiss watchmaker Longines.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] A special ceremony was organized for the clock inauguration at the station which was attended by the members of the organising committee of the Games and Scottish swimmer Michael Jamieson.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The total budget for the Games was £575.6 million.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] This figure included £472.3 million for Glasgow 2014 and £90 million for security.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Glasgow 2014 budget of £472.3 million was made up of £372 million of public money with the remainder coming from commercial income generated through sponsorship, ticket sales, broadcasting rights and merchandise sales.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The budget included contingency of £66.1 million, which was made up of a £42.3 million general contingency and £23.8 million special reserves.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] In February 2015, it was reported that the Games was delivered £35.5 million under budget.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The first round of the Games ticket sales were from 19 August to 16 September 2013.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Over two-thirds of tickets sold were priced at £25 or less.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The ticket price ranges for the opening ceremony and the closing ceremony were £40-£250 and £30-£200 respectively.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The 100m men's final event received over 100,000 applications which was the most of any event of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Boxing had the most expensive ticket of any sport in the Games whose category 1 tickets cost £120.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Ticketmaster was the official ticket services provider of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The medals for the Games were unveiled on 14 April 2014 at the Kelvingrove Art Gallery and Museum in Glasgow.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The medals were designed and hand-crafted by the renowned jeweller Jonathan Boyd and a team of specialist jewellery-makers from the prestigious Glasgow School of Art.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The hand-turned quaichs gifted to winning athletes and the carved ceremonial podiums were all created from local woods by Glasgow-based artisan Paul Hodgkiss.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Scottish designer Kerry Nixon designed the medalbearers' dresses.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Queen's Baton Relay began its 190,000 km journey on 9 October 2013.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The baton travelled via 70 nations and territories over 288 days before opening the games on 23 July 2014.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] At the ceremony, 32 volunteers from across Scotland carried the baton around Celtic Park Stadium after being nominated for giving their time to developing the nation's youth through sport.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The baton was then passed to Sir Chris Hoy, who delivered it to President of the Commonwealth Games Federation Prince Imran and the Queen who then declared the games open.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Queen's Baton was designed by the Glasgow-based firm 4c Design.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Adventurer Mark Beaumont presented a series of documentaries filmed on the relay for BBC One Scotland, there were also weekly updates for BBC News and a BBC News website and blog written by Mark.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Glasgow Airport was used to welcome and depart the athletes and officials of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The main terminal building of Glasgow Airport was upgraded at a cost of £17 million.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] During the games, spectators were encouraged to use the public transport, particularly for longer journeys as they make their way to the venues of the games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Glasgow 2014 ticket included access to local public transport services (trains, buses and Subway) to and from the venue on the day of the event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] In order to access those services, the spectators had to show the valid event ticket on request.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The spectators were also encouraged to walk or use bicycles instead of motor vehicles to reach the venues in order to avoid traffic jam.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The athletes were transported in minibuses or coaches, which used, where necessary, dedicated lanes – known as the Games Route Network – to ensure they were given priority over other traffic in a similar way buses are in bus lanes.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] These lanes formed part of a larger dedicated Games Route Network that was also used by the people working on the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Approximately 12,500 volunteers were hired for the Games out of over 50,000 applicants which was more than the number who applied for Melbourne 2006 and Manchester 2002.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The army of volunteers enlisted to help during the Games were known as Clyde-siders.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The uniforms for the volunteers were created by the outdoor clothing manufacturer Trespass.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] An integrated security team which involved Police Scotland, Glasgow 2014's Security team and private sector partners, was developed to manage the security and stewarding requirements for the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] More than 17,000 individuals were involved in this operation, where over 2,000 members were from the armed forces and the rest from the Police Scotland and 17 private sector companies.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The budget for the Games security was around £90 million.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The programme, which included about 2,000 performers, featured Karen Dunbar, John Barrowman, Amy Macdonald, Rod Stewart, Susan Boyle, Nicola Benedetti, Julie Fowlis, Eric Whitacre, and Pumeza Matshikiza, as well as a message from the International Space Station.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The ceremony began with a countdown and a recorded video message from Scottish actor Ewan McGregor, explaining the partnership between the Games and UNICEF.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Following the arrival of the Queen there was a flypast by the Red Arrows display team.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The venue featured the largest LED video screen in Europe, supplied by Sports Technology.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Scotland's then First Minister Alex Salmond welcomed the participants and spectators, and introduced a moment of silence in memory of the Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 disaster.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The final part of the Queen's Baton Relay was run by 32 Scottish volunteers nominated for giving their time to developing the nation's youth through sport.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The baton was then passed to Sir Chris Hoy, who delivered it to President of the Commonwealth Games Federation Prince Imran and the Queen.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The display of the message concealed within the baton was delayed by a difficulty in opening the device.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Games were launched in partnership with UNICEF, to save and change children's lives.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The ceremony was directed by David Zolkwer with David Proctor (Executive Producer) and Sarah Gardiner (Creative Producer).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The closing ceremony took a visual theme of a music festival, with performers, tents, and flags within the stadium.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The ceremony began with Scottish singer Lulu welcoming the athletes of the games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Scottish band Deacon Blue performed their signature song "Dignity".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] During this the workers of Glasgow were recognised as they paraded along the front of the main stand at Hampden, some on foot, others in their work vehicles.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Local band Prides performed their hit song "Messiah".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Speeches followed, with Prince Imran telling the crowd that the games were "pure dead brilliant", a local Glaswegian term.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The games were officially closed and handed over to the Gold Coast for 2018, who began their own performance with Australian singer Jessica Mauboy.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Kylie Minogue then performed a seven-hit songs set list, while the volunteer cast told the story of "a typical Glasgow night out".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Her costume was designed by Jean Paul Gaultier and headpiece designed by millinery designer Lara Jensen.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The show ended with Dougie MacLean performing Caledonia with the other performers, and a performance of "Auld Lang Syne".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The closing ceremony was directed by David Zolkwer with David Proctor (Executive Producer) and Sarah Gardiner (Creative Producer).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] There were 71 participating nations at the 2014 Commonwealth Games with approximately 4,950 competing athletes, making it one of the largest Commonwealth Games staged to date.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] On 7 October 2013, The Gambia, having withdrawn from the Commonwealth five days earlier, confirmed that it would not be taking part in the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The following table shows a summary of the competition schedule.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] A total of 18 sports and 261 medal events were contested at the 2014 Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] A record 22 para-sport events were contested in five different sports (athletics, cycling, lawn bowls, swimming and weightlifting) and para track cycling was held for the very first time.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Archery and tennis from the 2010 games were replaced on the sports programme with triathlon (who turned back after the 2010 absence) and judo (after eight years absence).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Among sport disciplines removed from 2010 include the walking events in athletics, synchronised swimming and Greco-Roman wrestling, while mountain biking also returned after the absence in Delhi.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The number of Shooting medal events also dropped from 44 in 2010 to 19.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Among new disciplines on the Commonwealth Games programme for the first time were the triathlon mixed relay event, more medal chances for women at shooting and the addition of women's boxing to the programme.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Only the top ten successful nations are displayed here.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The ranking in this table is consistent with International Olympic Committee convention in its published medal tables.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a "nation" is an entity represented by a Commonwealth Games Association).
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by their three-letter country code.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Two bronze medals were awarded in boxing, judo and wrestling, except for Women's freestyle 75 kg as only five competitors were entered in the event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Additionally, two bronze medals were awarded in the men's 100 m backstroke and women's pole vault as a result of a tie between two athletes.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] No bronze medal was awarded in the men's synchronized 10 metre platform as only four teams competed in the event.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Therefore, the total number of bronze medals is greater than the total number of gold or silver medals.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Sunset + Vine Global Television Host Broadcasting Limited (SVGTV), a joint venture between Sunset + Vine, subsidiary of Tinopolis, a Wales-based television production group and Australia-based television production company, Global Television served as the host broadcaster of the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The interim logo for the Games was first used during Glasgow's bid, with the "Candidate City" section removed following 9 November 2007, when the bid was approved.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The logo depicts two sprinters woven into a tartan motif, representing Scotland.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The logo also vaguely resembles the Clyde Auditorium, one of Glasgow's most recognisable landmarks.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The pattern, forming the Roman numerals XX, also represents the 20th edition of the Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The text is more specifically Glaswegian, with its stylised Mackintosh font.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] A flag featuring the logo was used extensively during the bid process.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The flag was flown above Merchant House in George Square daily.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The full Games brand identity was developed by Glasgow design studio Tangent Graphic, the lead creative agency between 2010 and 2014.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Tangent's first major project was the official sport Pictograms, launched on 23 July 2011, and they continued to deliver and influence every aspect of the Glasgow 2014 identity.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Tangent inherited the official logo which was designed by Marque Creative.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The logo was unveiled on Commonwealth Day, 8 March 2010.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] It was inspired by three factors, time, data and measurement.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Its rings are proportioned to represent the 20th Commonwealth Games, across 17 sports, over 11 days in 1 city.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] An animated version of the logo has also been produced.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] There is also a version of the logo in Scottish Gaelic.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The official website was built in phases, delivered by Dog Digital and Blonde.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Scottish art firm Artpistol were commissioned by the Glasgow 2014 Organising Committee to paint a series of murals across Glasgow to help celebrate and promote the Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The Big G is a standalone stage-set that was situated in George Square, Glasgow.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] It was unveiled in May 2014; with Glasgow City Council leader Gordon Matheson commenting that it provided an "opportunity for everyone – residents, visitors and spectators – to be part of the Games".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] British designing firm Evolve designed the Big G.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Clyde, an anthropomorphic thistle named after the river which flows through the centre of Glasgow, was the official mascot of the 2014 Commonwealth Games.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The mascot was designed by Beth Gilmour, who won a competition run by Glasgow 2014 for children to design the Mascot.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Beth's drawing was then brought to life by digital agency Nerv, who turned it into a commercial character, created a full backstory, gave it a name – Clyde – and created a website for him.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Clyde was finally revealed in a seven-minute animated film created by Nerv at a ceremony at BBC Scotland's headquarters in Glasgow.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] The organiser, Glasgow 2014, said the mascot's design was chosen because of its "Scottish symbolism and Glaswegian charm and likeability".
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] 25 life-size Clyde statues were erected at places of public interest across the city including the Glasgow Botanic Gardens, the Kelvingrove Art Gallery and at George Square.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] However following vandalism at a statue in the Govan area of the city, the statues were taken down.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] They are expected to be re-erected in secure areas.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] By the final day of the Games, over 50,000 Clyde mascot cuddly toys had been sold.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Due to popularity in the city, the Clyde mascots are currently proposed official mascots of the Glasgow City Council.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Nigeria's Chika Amalaha failed a doping test and was stripped of a gold medal in the women's 53 kg weightlifting.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] In the women's 400 metres final, Botswana's Amantle Montsho placed fourth; she was subsequently provisionally suspended pending the results of a B sample after failing a doping test.
[src:2014-commonwealth-games/2014-commonwealth-games] Montsho's B sample was reported as positive on 14 August 2014.
